research/history/logs/agent_round_0093.stdout.log:4620:research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0064.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The standard gated hyperparameter sweeps at K=128 are exhausted and the recent `AUXK_ALPHA=0.01` recovery check regressed, so the cleanest exploitation move is to reuse the best validated aux-free gated regime and probe the remaining adjacent lower-K point. Changing only K from the strongest K=128 anchor to K=32 tests whether the recovered gated recipe can strengthen the low-cost frontier without reopening blocked architecture paths.","summary":"Run a gated proxy comparison at `K=32` with the recovered aux-free signum recipe to test whether the stable K=128/K=64 regime also improves the remaining lower-K frontier point.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"gated","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This stays in exploitation mode on the strongest working family, avoids further exhausted LR/aux/EF sweeps at K=128, and changes a single dimension relative to the best anchor. The main risk is that K=32 remains too far from the quality target, but this is still the most informative remaining low-risk sweep inside the validated gated regime.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"gated"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0"},{"key":"K","value":"32"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["The gated K=128 recovery check with `AUXK_ALPHA=0.01` regressed badly, so the aux-free regime remains the best current working anchor for exploitation.","Standard gated LR, aux, and expansion sweeps are exhausted at K=128, so the most defensible remaining exploitation move is to map the adjacent K frontier under the recovered aux-free recipe.","This round keeps the family and optimization fixed and changes only K to test whether the restored gated regime improves the unresolved K=32 tradeoff."],"next_hypotheses":["If gated K=32 with `AUXK_ALPHA=0` improves over the current K=32 point, keep the aux-free regime alive across the low-K frontier.","If K=32 regresses, treat `AUXK_ALPHA=0` as beneficial mainly for K=64/128 and keep the canonical K=32 recipe when needed.","If the low-K gated sweep is exhausted without meaningful gains, shift the next round back toward architecture exploration once crash pressure is no longer dominant."],"primary_variable":"k"}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0093.stdout.log:4627:research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0021.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"JumpReLU local search appears exhausted, and reverting to the fundamentally different plain top-k SAE may provide a cleaner reconstruction-support tradeoff at K=128 under the same strong optimization settings, serving as a robust architecture reset after the failed gated launch attempts.","summary":"Switch from stalled JumpReLU tuning to a proxy top-k architecture run at K=128 while keeping the strongest validated training settings fixed for a clean architecture comparison.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"quality","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline_comparison","self_review":"This satisfies the requirement to try a fundamentally different architecture approach after prolonged stagnation, while avoiding the invalid gated-only overrides that caused recent crashes. The main risk is top-k underperforming JumpReLU, but it is the cleanest valid architecture pivot available without editing code.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Recent gated attempts failed at the launcher interface due to invalid env overrides, so a different architecture probe should avoid architecture-specific override keys unless confirmed valid.","Eight non-improving rounds indicate the current JumpReLU search direction is fundamentally stalled.","This round uses the plain top-k SAE as a clean architecture reset under the same best-known training regime to measure whether JumpReLU-specific gating is part of the quality bottleneck."],"next_hypotheses":["If top-k improves proxy FVU, promote to full and then stabilize the top-k family before revisiting cost or smaller-K tradeoffs.","If top-k is competitive but not better, compare its runtime and stability against JumpReLU to decide whether it is a better base for further architecture work.","If top-k is clearly worse, conclude that a stronger new family is needed and plan a code-backed architecture exploration round rather than more JumpReLU-local parameter sweeps."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0093.stdout.log:4637:research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0051.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Stability has returned on the gated path, and the K=64 point was reconfirmed exactly in both proxy and full. The next least-risk informative move is to refresh the adjacent lower-cost gated Pareto point at K=32 under the same strongest regime, keeping architecture, optimizer, LR, AUXK, and expansion fixed so only K changes.","summary":"Run a gated proxy stabilization pass on the current best EF=16 signum configuration with `K=32`, keeping LR=1.6e-3 and AUXK_ALPHA=0.01 fixed.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"gated","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This keeps the session on the stable best-known family, changes only one parameter, and updates the next lower-K Pareto point after K=64 was reconfirmed cleanly. The main risk is low novelty because K=32 is already on the frontier, but it is still the safest informative move before reintroducing any blocked architecture work.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"gated"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.01"},{"key":"K","value":"32"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 50 restored a clean working baseline: gated K=64 reproduced its prior proxy and full behavior under the strongest stable regime.","This round stays on the same gated recipe and changes only K, moving to the adjacent lower-cost Pareto point at K=32.","After repeated factorized-topk crashes, continued progress should come from stable gated runs until there is a concrete implementation plan for any new architecture attempt."],"next_hypotheses":["If K=32 matches or improves its prior proxy behavior, keep the gated low-K frontier confirmed and consider cost-focused comparisons within the stable family.","If K=32 regresses unexpectedly under the same stable recipe, treat recent results as noisy and return to the exact K=128 anchor to recheck baseline stability.","If stability remains clean after this round, resume broader architecture exploration only with an implementation plan that avoids the recent unregistered-architecture failure mode."],"primary_variable":"k"}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0093.stdout.log:4671:research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0038.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The last round showed the gated low-K capacity cut was a real quality regression, and the search has now gone several rounds without advancing an incubating alternative family. The least-bad informative move is to get a real proxy read on the already-implemented `group_topk` family at K=128 under the strongest current training regime, removing the unsupported `GROUP_TOPK_SIZE` override that caused the earlier policy crashes. This will finally test whether local winner-take-all competition can beat other non-gated support selectors on anchor-quality rather than being discarded for an execution-layer mismatch.","summary":"Run the first real proxy comparison for `group_topk` at K=128 using the current strongest gated training regime, but without the unsupported `GROUP_TOPK_SIZE` env override that caused the earlier crashes.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"group_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This advances an incubating family instead of spending another round on weak local gated tuning, and it specifically resolves prior `group_topk` crashes as execution-layer issues rather than architectural evidence. The main risk is that hard local competition may still be too restrictive to challenge gated on FVU, but one clean proxy run is necessary before deciding whether to retire or stabilize this family.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"group_topk"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.01"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Rounds 32-33 did not provide architectural evidence on `group_topk`; they were rejected because `GROUP_TOPK_SIZE` is not an allowed execution-layer override.","This round retries `group_topk` with only allowed overrides so the family gets its first actual proxy measurement under the current strongest K=128 training regime.","Using the gated anchor settings at K=128 isolates architecture as the primary changed variable and gives a clean read on whether local competition is a viable quality direction."],"next_hypotheses":["If `group_topk` is competitive with gated at K=128, keep the family alive and follow with a code-round that softens or enriches the grouped selection mechanism inside `sparsify/`, since group-size sweeps are not exposed by the execution layer.","If `group_topk` is clearly worse on quality under a normal run, retire hard local grouping and move to a more expressive multi-branch or factorized encoder family instead of more support-ranking variants.","If `group_topk` is mediocre on FVU but materially better on runtime or memory, evaluate it as a cost-quality tradeoff family before discarding it."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0093.stdout.log:4710:research/history_archive/15_20260326_190606/logs/agent_action_0008.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"`K=96` established a valid smaller-support `topk` point without crashing, so the next single-question K-stage move is to measure whether the cost-quality slope stays acceptable when support is cut more materially. Dropping from `K=96` to `K=64` on the same tuned signum recipe will show whether LUTurbo can gain a more meaningful selection-cost reduction before reconstruction degrades too sharply.","summary":"Keep the `topk` mainline recipe fixed at `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, and `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, and change only `K` from `96` to `64`. This continues the K-stage mapping in the same family and answers one concrete question: whether the first nontrivial support cut beyond `K=96` still yields an acceptable Pareto tradeoff for deployment-oriented cost reduction.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"smaller_k","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This respects the single-variable rule and stays on the active family while extending the K frontier in the prescribed final stage. The main risk is that `K=64` may fall off the quality cliff, so the result should be judged by the whole curve and by whether the extra support reduction is large enough to justify any observed FVU loss.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"K","value":"64"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"2.0e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"},{"key":"DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD","value":"10000000"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"0"},{"key":"HOOKPOINTS","value":"layers.[3].self_attn.o_proj"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["`topk` now has two EF=12 frontier anchors under the tuned signum recipe: `K=128` at `FVU=0.4522051215171814` and `K=96` at `FVU=0.4886302351951599`.","Round 8 continues the K stage by testing `K=64` under the same `topk` signum recipe to estimate whether a larger support reduction can still be deployment-viable.","Interpret this round by both curve shape and Pareto value: even if FVU worsens, `K=64` may still matter if degradation is gradual rather than cliff-like."],"next_hypotheses":["If `K=64` remains reasonably close to the `K=96` point, continue to `K=32` on the same recipe to map the low-K slope.","If `K=64` shows a sharp quality cliff, stop forcing lower K on plain `topk` and treat new family search as the more promising route for LUTurbo cost reduction.","If `K=64` is borderline, compare its curve shape against `K=96` to decide whether the lower-K regime deserves an LR retune before abandoning it."],"primary_variable":"k"}
