research/history/logs/agent_round_0077.stdout.log:706:research/history_archive/rollback_to_pre_round38_20260321_124110/logs/agent_action_0040.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The best current working point is gated K=128 EF=16 with signum, LR=1.6e-3, and AUXK_ALPHA=0.01. Since lowering AUXK_ALPHA from 0.03125 to 0.01 materially improved both proxy and full FVU, the next lowest-risk recovery move is to remove the auxiliary penalty entirely. Testing AUXK_ALPHA=0 on the same gated K=128 anchor may further reduce reconstruction interference and improve FVU without introducing architectural or launch instability.","summary":"Run a proxy gated K=128 stabilization pass on the current best configuration with AUXK_ALPHA reduced from 0.01 to 0.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"gated","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This respects crash-recovery constraints by keeping the strongest validated architecture and changing only one dynamic parameter on the current best K=128 baseline. The main risk is worse feature health from removing auxiliary pressure, but proxy is the right tier for that check and LR=2e-4 looks less defensible because lower-LR gated sweeps already regressed badly.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"gated"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["For gated K=128 EF=16, reducing AUXK_ALPHA from 0.03125 to 0.01 improved the frontier, so the next conservative recovery probe is the same anchor with AUXK disabled entirely.","Keeping architecture, K, expansion factor, optimizer, and LR fixed isolates AUXK_ALPHA as the only changed variable on the strongest validated baseline.","Given the earlier failures at lower learning rates, AUXK_ALPHA=0 is a more defensible stability-oriented quality probe than continuing the low-LR sweep."],"next_hypotheses":["If gated K=128 with AUXK_ALPHA=0 improves proxy FVU, promote it to full and treat no-auxk as the new mainline gated anchor.","If AUXK_ALPHA=0 is slightly worse but healthy, restore AUXK_ALPHA=0.01 and consider a small gated-specific support-shaping probe such as GATED_TEMPERATURE on the same K=128 baseline.","If AUXK_ALPHA=0 clearly hurts training or feature health, keep AUXK_ALPHA=0.01 as the stabilized default and end this local auxk reduction branch."],"primary_variable":"other_param"}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0077.stdout.log:714:research/history_archive/history_20260320_152535/logs/agent_action_0005.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The routed_group_topk proxy crash was caused by an optimizer implementation bug, not by the architecture itself: ScheduleFreeWrapperReference writes per-parameter state before delegating to Adam, which makes Adam skip its own state initialization and crash on step 2. If Adam is run without the incompatible wrapper, the same rotated routed_group_topk prototype at K=128 should finally produce a usable quality signal and may beat the rotated topk proxy anchor on FVU.","summary":"Fix the Adam path in sparsify/trainer.py so proxy experiments can run routed_group_topk with Adam without crashing, then rerun the same rotated routed_group_topk prototype at K=128 to get an actual quality read instead of discarding the family on an implementation artifact.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"rotated_routed_group_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This follows the program guidance to treat recent crashes as implementation issues before drawing architecture conclusions. The edit is narrowly scoped under sparsify/, preserves the fixed execution layer, and keeps one coherent hypothesis: unblocking Adam for the same family/config that previously failed before producing metrics. The main risk is that routed_group_topk may still underperform on quality once it runs, but this round cleanly separates that question from the optimizer bug.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"routed_group_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"1"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"},{"key":"LR","value":"3e-4"},{"key":"NUM_GROUPS","value":"32"},{"key":"ACTIVE_GROUPS","value":"8"}],"touched_files":["sparsify/trainer.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Read research/program.md before deciding; the right response to the last round is a code fix because the routed_group_topk run crashed before yielding any architectural evidence.","The round 4 crash is reproducibly explained by an optimizer bug: ScheduleFreeWrapperReference populates per-parameter state keys (z/x/y) before calling Adam, so Adam sees a non-empty state dict and then throws KeyError on missing exp_avg.","Updated sparsify/trainer.py so Adam uses a plain torch.optim.Adam path while SignSGD keeps the ScheduleFree wrapper; this preserves the existing signum behavior and unblocks Adam-based family exploration."],"next_hypotheses":["If routed_group_topk now runs and shows promising proxy FVU, keep the family alive with a stabilization sweep over num_groups, active_groups, and LR.","If routed_group_topk now runs but is clearly weak on proxy FVU, escalate to a different encoder family such as a factorized or multi-branch routed encoder instead of spending more rounds on weak local tuning.","If additional optimizer-specific issues appear for Adam-based families, isolate them as implementation bugs before interpreting the quality result."]}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0077.stdout.log:718:research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0019.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The round-18 refined_topk crash was caused by a mixed-precision implementation bug in the ridge solve, not by evidence against the architecture. Running the small support-wise solve in float32 and casting the refined coefficients back to the model dtype should make the family trainable under bf16 autocast, allowing a valid proxy read on whether coefficient refitting can lower FVU at K=128.","summary":"Keep refined_topk alive for one crash-recovery follow-up. The architecture stays the same, but its coefficient-refinement solve is now executed in a stable float32 path so the proxy run can test the actual quality hypothesis instead of failing on dtype mismatch.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"refined_topk","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This is a narrow implementation-fix round on the most recent crashing family, which is the right move after a first-run failure with a clear stack trace. The main risk is that the architecture may still be weak even after the fix, but a clean rerun is more informative than abandoning the family based on a bf16/autocast bug.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"refined_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"}],"touched_files":["/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/refined_topk_sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Round 19 fixes a refined_topk mixed-precision bug: the support-wise ridge solve now runs in float32 and casts refined coefficients back to the model dtype.","The refined_topk crash in round 18 came from a bf16/float32 mismatch inside torch.linalg.solve under autocast, so that round should not be treated as architecture evidence.","A local bf16 import/forward/backward sanity check passed for the fixed refined_topk implementation before handing control back to the runtime."],"next_hypotheses":["If the fixed refined_topk yields a meaningful proxy FVU gain, follow with a family-specific stabilization pass on regularization strength or support source before considering promotion.","If refined_topk now runs normally but lands near the recent 0.275 proxy plateau, conclude that coefficient refitting alone is insufficient and pivot to a genuinely different encoder family next round."]}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0077.stdout.log:723:research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0020.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Crash recovery and policy both point to a narrow param-only move: keep the current best working proxy configuration in hybrid_topk fixed and test whether it remains viable when K is reduced from 128 to 64. This is the required first step in K exploration, and it isolates the effect of sparsity level without confounding architecture or optimizer changes.","summary":"Run a proxy K=64 check on the current best working hybrid_topk configuration, holding the rest of the known-stable proxy settings fixed so this round cleanly measures the first smaller-K point.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"hybrid_topk","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This follows the runtime constraints exactly: no code edits, one coherent hypothesis, proxy-first, and explicit K exploration after recent crashes. I am using the best working proxy anchor rather than introducing any new family or secondary tuning, so the result should be interpretable even if K=64 regresses.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"hybrid_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"64"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"},{"key":"LR","value":"8e-4"},{"key":"HOOKPOINTS","value":"layers.[3].self_attn.o_proj"},{"key":"BATCH_SIZE","value":"1"},{"key":"GRAD_ACC_STEPS","value":"8"},{"key":"MICRO_ACC_STEPS","value":"1"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"},{"key":"DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD","value":"10000000"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"false"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 20 obeys crash-recovery mode and performs a param-only K exploration run on the best working hybrid_topk proxy setup.","The first required smaller-K probe is K=64, with the rest of the stable hybrid_topk proxy configuration held fixed for interpretability.","This round is intended as the first step before a likely K=32 follow-up, unless K=64 shows an unexpected stability or quality failure that changes the plan."],"next_hypotheses":["If hybrid_topk at K=64 is stable and reasonably competitive, run the same configuration at K=32 next to complete the required smaller-K sweep.","If K=64 collapses badly or becomes unstable, keep the architecture fixed and consider a minor recovery adjustment within hybrid_topk rather than introducing a new family immediately."],"primary_variable":"k"}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0077.stdout.log:743:research/history_archive/07_20260321_004359/logs/agent_action_0006.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The stabilized factorized_topk crash was caused by an implementation bug in the widened hidden-path projection, not by the architecture itself. Fix the hidden-to-latent projection and rerun the same K=128 factorized_topk stabilization pass to recover a valid quality signal.","summary":"Round 5 produced a shape-mismatch crash inside factorized_topk after the widening edit, so the next move is a direct bug-fix rerun rather than abandoning the family. This keeps the hypothesis narrow: validate the intended wider gated factorized encoder before making any new architectural decision.","change_type":"edit_architecture","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"factorized_topk","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This is the correct response to the last round because the failure was a concrete code bug, not a training-quality outcome. The rerun is still only worth one more round; if the fixed version remains poor, this branch should be deprioritized.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"factorized_topk"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"}],"touched_files":["/root/sparsify-ascend/sparsify/factorized_topk_sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Round 5 factorized_topk crashed due to a hidden-to-latent shape mismatch in the widened encoder path, so that result should not be treated as architectural evidence.","Round 6 fixes factorized_topk by adding an explicit hidden-to-latent projection and excluding the unused base encoder from optimization before re-running the same stabilization test."],"next_hypotheses":["If the fixed factorized_topk now yields a valid proxy improvement, keep incubating the family with quality-focused tuning.","If the fixed factorized_topk still performs poorly under normal runtime, stop spending rounds on current built-in families and move to a genuinely new encoder design."]}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0077.stdout.log:744:research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0050.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Crash recovery mode requires returning to the best known working gated path with only a minor parameter adjustment. The safest informative move is to reuse the strongest stable recipe and probe the adjacent lower-K point `K=64`, which is already a validated Pareto setting and avoids the blocked architecture-code path entirely.","summary":"Run a gated proxy stabilization pass on the current best EF=16 signum configuration with `K=64`, keeping LR=1.6e-3 and AUXK_ALPHA=0.01 fixed.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"gated","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This follows crash-recovery constraints exactly by avoiding code edits and using the strongest validated family with one small parameter change. The main risk is limited novelty because K=64 is already known, but this is the least risky way to recover a clean signal after consecutive architecture-path crashes.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"gated"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.01"},{"key":"K","value":"64"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Crash recovery mode requires a param-only round on the current best working configuration, so this round returns to the stable gated recipe.","The `factorized_topk` path has now crashed repeatedly for implementation-layer reasons, so it should not be touched again until session stability is re-established.","Using gated K=64 preserves the strongest known architecture and training regime while testing a previously healthy lower-cost Pareto point."],"next_hypotheses":["If the K=64 proxy run is healthy and matches its prior behavior, keep using the gated family for recovery until crashes stop.","If K=64 regresses unexpectedly under the same stable regime, return to the exact K=128 anchor on the next round to separate runtime noise from configuration effects.","If stability is restored after this round, resume broader exploration only with a clear implementation plan that avoids the recent factorized-topk registration failure mode."],"primary_variable":"k"}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0077.stdout.log:745:research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0042.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"After multiple rounds dominated by gated-local tuning and unresolved crash recovery, the most informative next move is to advance an already-incubating alternate family rather than spend another round near the current gated anchor. A clean `topk` K=128 proxy run under the current strongest gated training regime tests whether simpler support selection benefits more from the improved optimizer and regularization settings than it did in earlier comparisons.","summary":"Run a fresh `topk` K=128 proxy mainline comparison using the current strongest signum gated regime to see whether the improved training setup materially closes the quality gap for the incubating top-k family.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline_comparison","self_review":"This is a better use of the round than another gated-adjacent parameter tweak because the search has gone too long without advancing a distinct family, and `topk` already has working runs that can cleanly absorb the stronger regime. The main risk is that top-k remains well behind gated on FVU, but that negative result is still useful because it would retire a lingering incumbent alternative and narrow future exploration toward more novel architectures.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.01"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["The search has now gone eight rounds without advancing a new family, so architecture exploration should take priority over more local gated tuning.","`topk` remains incubating with older K=128 proxy evidence taken under weaker regimes, so it deserves one clean comparison against the current strongest training setup before being retired or promoted.","This round keeps the regime fixed to the current gated anchor settings and changes only architecture, giving a direct read on whether simpler global top-k selection benefits from the newer training recipe."],"next_hypotheses":["If `topk` improves materially over its prior proxy results and is competitive with gated at K=128, promote it to full and begin family-specific stabilization from this stronger anchor.","If `topk` runs normally but remains clearly worse than gated, retire it from near-term focus and move to a more expressive new architecture family.","If `topk` is still worse on FVU but shows meaningfully better runtime or memory behavior, keep it alive as a cost-quality tradeoff family rather than a main quality contender."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0077.stdout.log:748:research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0030.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The routed family did not get a fair read because its initial support selection was too close to baseline top-k and tripped the identical-to-baseline guard. Making routed support depend on an independently initialized router with a direct, non-monotone routing bonus should produce a genuine architecture signal in proxy and reveal whether separate support selection can outperform the stalled gated search.","summary":"Fix the routed prototype so its initial routing behavior is observably different from baseline top-k, then rerun routed in proxy at K=128 under the current strongest training regime.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"quality","family_name":"routed","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This is a coherent architecture follow-up under severe stagnation: it repairs a blocked fundamentally different family instead of spending another round on minor parameter tuning. The main risk is that routed still underperforms on quality, but the previous crash was not informative, so this code-fix probe is higher value than more local gated adjustments.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"routed"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":["sparsify/sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Adjusted routed initialization so the router is independently initialized instead of near-copying the magnitude encoder, avoiding baseline-equivalent startup behavior.","Changed routed support scoring to include a direct router bonus, making selection meaningfully different from plain top-k while still decoding with gated magnitudes.","Local sanity checks now show routed top-k indices and top activations differ from baseline at initialization, and forward/backward both succeed."],"next_hypotheses":["If routed now runs cleanly and beats gated proxy materially, promote it and begin routed-specific stabilization as the main architecture path.","If routed runs but remains clearly worse, retire this version of the family and redirect architecture exploration elsewhere.","If routed quality is competitive but runtime is poor, keep the family alive and follow with a performance-focused code pass rather than discarding it on throughput alone."],"primary_variable":"code_fix"}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0077.stdout.log:751:research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0022.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Top-k was only modestly competitive and still far from the K=128 quality target, so the next fundamentally different probe is the gated SAE family using only launcher-safe overrides; separating support selection from magnitude may recover cleaner latent routing than both JumpReLU and plain top-k.","summary":"Launch a proxy gated-family prototype at K=128 using the strongest validated training regime, but avoid architecture-specific override keys that previously caused invalid-env crashes.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"quality","family_name":"gated","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This keeps the round focused on a real architecture change rather than another exhausted local sweep, and it directly addresses the recent gated launch failures by using only confirmed-safe env overrides. The main risk is that gated remains worse than top-k and JumpReLU, but that is the most informative remaining architecture probe available without code changes.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"gated"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Top-k produced a clean proxy run but remained far above the current full K=128 JumpReLU frontier, so a stronger architecture change is still needed.","Recent gated crashes were caused by invalid env overrides rather than confirmed model failure, so the family deserves one clean retry with only generic override keys.","This round tests whether gated routing can provide a more meaningful architecture departure than plain top-k while keeping the optimization regime fixed."],"next_hypotheses":["If gated runs cleanly and improves proxy FVU, stabilize the family with a follow-up that tunes gate-specific parameters or promotes to full if the gain is large enough.","If gated runs cleanly but is still uncompetitive, conclude that the current non-code architecture set is exhausted and plan a code-backed new family next.","If gated still crashes under launcher-safe overrides, retire it as an execution-layer mismatch and focus future architecture exploration on families that can be expressed with the current valid override surface."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0077.stdout.log:755:research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0062.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"`residual_topk` still has no quality signal because the latest prototype attempt failed at the same architecture-selection gate before training began. The smallest informative move remains a narrow code-fix round inside `sparsify/` that explicitly registers `residual_topk` in config validation and SAE class dispatch, so the intended K=128 proxy prototype can finally clear selection and reach a real sanity/training signal.","summary":"Fix `residual_topk` architecture registration and dispatch under `sparsify/`, then rerun the same K=128 proxy prototype under the current signum baseline.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"residual_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This keeps the round focused on the repeated blocker instead of spending another cycle on exhausted gated sweeps. The main risk is that registration is only the first missing piece, but resolving the concrete selection failure is still the cleanest next step and preserves comparability of the intended prototype run.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"residual_topk"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.01"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":["sparsify/config.py","sparsify/sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Round 61 repeated the same `Unknown architecture: 'residual_topk'` failure, so the family is still blocked at architecture registration rather than judged on quality or runtime.","The stable gated frontier remains useful as an anchor, but further local gated sweeps are currently less informative than unblocking a new family that still has no valid proxy signal.","This round should remain a minimal blocker-removal pass limited to making `residual_topk` selectable and constructible by the existing execution layer."],"next_hypotheses":["If `residual_topk` clears sanity and yields a competitive proxy result, keep the family alive and tune its internal allocation next.","If `residual_topk` runs but is clearly uncompetitive, archive it quickly and move to a different architecture family.","If the run still fails after registration and dispatch are fixed, treat the remaining issue as deeper architecture compatibility and switch to another new family rather than returning to more gated local tuning."],"primary_variable":"code_fix"}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0077.stdout.log:764:research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0046.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The obvious gated one-parameter sweep is now exhausted after clean regressions on both lower LR and lower expansion, so the next least-bad informative move is to unblock the incubating `factorized_topk` family rather than introduce another fresh direction. Its only evidence so far is a `sanity_failed` prototype, which should be treated as an architecture-compatibility issue, not a quality result. A narrow code fix inside `sparsify/` to make `factorized_topk` forward/backward compatible with the runtime should recover one valid proxy measurement at K=128 under the existing strongest regime.","summary":"Fix the `factorized_topk` implementation in `sparsify/` so it passes sanity, then rerun the same K=128 proxy prototype under the current signum baseline.","change_type":"edit_perf_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"factorized_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This follows the current priority order: resolve the blocked sanity failure on an already-incubating family before expanding the search space again. The main risk is spending a round on implementation recovery for a family that still underperforms, but one clean run is necessary before making any architecture judgment.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"factorized_topk"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.01"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":["sparsify/config.py","sparsify/sparse_coder.py"],"notes_to_memory":["The gated exploitation sweep has now tested the remaining obvious one-parameter moves at K=128 and both lower LR and lower expansion regressed cleanly.","`factorized_topk` still has no usable quality signal because its first prototype failed at sanity, so it should not be treated as an architecture-quality miss yet.","This round keeps the original `factorized_topk` proxy target and changes only the architecture code needed for forward/backward compatibility under the fixed runtime."],"next_hypotheses":["If the repaired `factorized_topk` run completes and beats plain `topk`, keep the family alive and stabilize its internal factorization width or activation design next.","If the repaired run completes normally but remains far behind gated, retire shallow factorization and move to a different encoder-expressivity direction such as low-rank-plus-residual or routed multi-branch designs.","If `factorized_topk` still fails sanity after the focused fix, conclude that this prototype path is currently not viable in the stack and shift effort to another architecture family with a cleaner integration path."],"primary_variable":"code_fix"}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0077.stdout.log:765:research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0064.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The standard gated hyperparameter sweeps at K=128 are exhausted and the recent `AUXK_ALPHA=0.01` recovery check regressed, so the cleanest exploitation move is to reuse the best validated aux-free gated regime and probe the remaining adjacent lower-K point. Changing only K from the strongest K=128 anchor to K=32 tests whether the recovered gated recipe can strengthen the low-cost frontier without reopening blocked architecture paths.","summary":"Run a gated proxy comparison at `K=32` with the recovered aux-free signum recipe to test whether the stable K=128/K=64 regime also improves the remaining lower-K frontier point.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"gated","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This stays in exploitation mode on the strongest working family, avoids further exhausted LR/aux/EF sweeps at K=128, and changes a single dimension relative to the best anchor. The main risk is that K=32 remains too far from the quality target, but this is still the most informative remaining low-risk sweep inside the validated gated regime.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"gated"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0"},{"key":"K","value":"32"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["The gated K=128 recovery check with `AUXK_ALPHA=0.01` regressed badly, so the aux-free regime remains the best current working anchor for exploitation.","Standard gated LR, aux, and expansion sweeps are exhausted at K=128, so the most defensible remaining exploitation move is to map the adjacent K frontier under the recovered aux-free recipe.","This round keeps the family and optimization fixed and changes only K to test whether the restored gated regime improves the unresolved K=32 tradeoff."],"next_hypotheses":["If gated K=32 with `AUXK_ALPHA=0` improves over the current K=32 point, keep the aux-free regime alive across the low-K frontier.","If K=32 regresses, treat `AUXK_ALPHA=0` as beneficial mainly for K=64/128 and keep the canonical K=32 recipe when needed.","If the low-K gated sweep is exhausted without meaningful gains, shift the next round back toward architecture exploration once crash pressure is no longer dominant."],"primary_variable":"k"}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0077.stdout.log:766:research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0044.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The cleanest next move is to stay on the strongest stable gated K=128 anchor and test a lower learning rate as a single-variable stabilization sweep. If the current `1.6e-3` regime is slightly overshooting, `2e-4` may improve reconstruction quality without changing architecture, sparsity mechanism, or expansion.","summary":"Run a gated K=128 proxy stabilization pass at `LR=2e-4` on the current EF=16 signum baseline to test whether a lower learning rate improves FVU on the main quality anchor.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"quality","family_name":"gated","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This keeps the round narrow, avoids mixing code and architecture changes, and targets the current best validated family with a plausible quality-oriented hyperparameter sweep. The main risk is undertraining in proxy, but that still gives a useful bound on whether lower-LR gated tuning is worth further attention.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"gated"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"2e-4"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.01"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["The most recent valid alternate-family result left `topk` clearly behind gated, so this round returns to the best stable gated anchor for a one-variable sweep.","Older crashes should not be treated as architecture-quality evidence, so this round avoids reopening unstable code paths and instead seeks a clean proxy signal.","Keeping architecture, K, optimizer, AUXK, and expansion fixed isolates learning rate as the only changed variable on the strongest current baseline."],"next_hypotheses":["If `LR=2e-4` improves proxy FVU, promote it to full and treat lower-LR gated training as the new stabilization candidate.","If `LR=2e-4` is worse but training is healthy, keep `1.6e-3` as the gated LR anchor and test the remaining expansion-factor sweep only if exploitation continues.","If `LR=2e-4` undertrains badly, conclude that remaining gated gains are unlikely to come from lower LR and resume broader architecture exploration after closing any required sweep points."],"primary_variable":"lr"}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0077.stdout.log:768:research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0020.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Returning to the best known working JumpReLU K=128 configuration and modestly increasing AUXK_ALPHA to 0.0625 may improve training stability and feature health without changing the core architecture or optimization regime, potentially recovering some proxy quality after the recent stalled sweeps.","summary":"Use the current best working JumpReLU K=128 setup as the stability anchor and make one minor parameter adjustment by testing AUXK_ALPHA=0.0625 in proxy.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"quality","family_name":"jumprelu","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This respects crash-recovery constraints by avoiding code edits and new architectures, and it returns to the strongest validated configuration with a single conservative parameter change. The main risk is that higher auxk may over-regularize reconstruction, but it is a safer stability-oriented probe than another architecture shift.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"jumprelu"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0625"},{"key":"JUMPRELU_INIT_THRESHOLD","value":"0.15"},{"key":"JUMPRELU_BANDWIDTH","value":"0.1"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Crash-recovery mode requires returning to the best known working configuration and limiting the round to a minor parameter-only adjustment.","This round restores the strongest JumpReLU K=128 baseline and tests a slightly stronger auxiliary dead-feature objective for a stability-oriented probe.","If AUXK_ALPHA=0.0625 does not help, the remaining conservative fallback is an LR reduction on the same baseline rather than another architecture change."],"next_hypotheses":["If AUXK_ALPHA=0.0625 improves proxy FVU, promote to full and treat the higher-auxk regime as the new stable JumpReLU anchor.","If AUXK_ALPHA=0.0625 is worse but training remains healthy, test LR=2e-4 on the same restored baseline as the next stability-oriented adjustment.","If stability problems persist even on the restored baseline, pause architecture exploration and continue only with conservative recovery steps around the known-good JumpReLU configuration."],"primary_variable":"other_param"}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0077.stdout.log:772:research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0034.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"In crash recovery mode, the safest informative move is to return to the best known working gated K=128 configuration and make the smallest remaining stabilization adjustment. A milder auxiliary pressure of AUXK_ALPHA=0.01 may preserve the strong gated baseline while avoiding the degradation seen at 0.0625, giving a cleaner read on whether the current anchor is slightly over-regularized.","summary":"Run a proxy stabilization pass on the best gated K=128 EF=16 configuration with AUXK_ALPHA reduced from 0.03125 to 0.01.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"stability","family_name":"gated","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This follows crash recovery requirements by using the current best working architecture with a single minor parameter change and no code edits. The main risk is that this remains another non-improving local probe, but it is the lowest-risk unresolved stabilization axis around the strongest validated baseline.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"gated"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.01"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Crash recovery mode shifted the search back to the strongest validated gated K=128 baseline rather than continuing architecture exploration.","The higher AUXK_ALPHA=0.0625 probe was worse, so this round tests the opposite low-regularization direction with the smallest reasonable change.","This run isolates auxiliary-loss pressure as the only changed variable on the current best working configuration."],"next_hypotheses":["If AUXK_ALPHA=0.01 improves proxy FVU or training stability, promote it to full as the new gated stabilization candidate.","If AUXK_ALPHA=0.01 is also worse, conclude that the current gated anchor is not improved by AUXK retuning and keep the original 0.03125 setting as the stable baseline.","If this run shows instability despite using the best known working setup, continue crash recovery with another minimal gated parameter adjustment rather than returning to architecture exploration immediately."],"primary_variable":"other_param"}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0077.stdout.log:776:research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0040.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"In crash recovery mode, the safest informative move is to return to the current best working gated K=128 configuration and make the smallest remaining stabilization adjustment. Setting AUXK_ALPHA from 0.01 to 0 tests whether the new gated anchor is still slightly over-regularized while keeping architecture, K, expansion factor, optimizer, and learning rate fixed.","summary":"Run a proxy stabilization pass on the best gated K=128 EF=16 configuration with AUXK disabled to test whether pure reconstruction training can improve the current anchor without changing the core regime.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"quality","family_name":"gated","family_stage":"stabilize","self_review":"This follows crash-recovery requirements by using the strongest validated configuration with one minor parameter change and no code edits. The main risk is that removing auxk hurts feature health or quality, but it is the cleanest remaining stability-oriented probe on the current best baseline.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"gated"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"16"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Crash recovery mode requires returning to the best known working configuration and limiting the round to a minor parameter-only adjustment.","The gated K=128 EF=16 AUXK_ALPHA=0.01 setting remains the strongest validated full baseline, so this round probes the adjacent zero-auxk point for possible over-regularization.","Keeping architecture, K, expansion factor, optimizer, and learning rate fixed isolates AUXK_ALPHA as the only changed variable on the current anchor."],"next_hypotheses":["If AUXK_ALPHA=0 improves proxy FVU, promote it to full and treat auxk-free gated training as the new stabilization candidate.","If AUXK_ALPHA=0 is worse but training remains healthy, restore AUXK_ALPHA=0.01 and test a nearby small nonzero value only if policy still requires stability-first tuning.","If AUXK removal degrades quality clearly, keep AUXK_ALPHA=0.01 as the gated default and resume broader exploration only after crash recovery ends."],"primary_variable":"other_param"}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0077.stdout.log:782:research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0019.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"JumpReLU tuning appears fundamentally stalled, so the next credible move is to test the gated SAE family at K=128, where a separate sigmoid routing branch may learn cleaner support patterns than JumpReLU and reduce FVU under the same strong optimization settings.","summary":"Switch from exhausted JumpReLU sweeps to a proxy gated-family prototype at K=128 using the current best optimizer and training settings as the control.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"quality","family_name":"gated","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This satisfies the severe-stagnation requirement to leave minor JumpReLU tweaks and try a fundamentally different architecture. The main risk is another gated-family failure, but that is more informative now than continuing a search direction that has stalled for six rounds.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"gated"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"},{"key":"GATED_TEMPERATURE","value":"1.0"},{"key":"GATED_INIT_LOGIT","value":"2.0"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Six consecutive non-improving rounds indicate the local JumpReLU search direction is exhausted for now.","This round promotes the incubating gated family back into active testing as the required fundamentally different architecture probe.","Keeping the best-known training regime fixed isolates whether routing design, rather than another optimizer tweak, is the missing ingredient for lower FVU."],"next_hypotheses":["If gated improves proxy FVU at acceptable throughput, stabilize the family by tuning gate-specific parameters such as temperature or init_logit.","If gated shows quality promise but runtime regresses, follow with a code/performance round instead of discarding the architecture outright.","If gated is clearly worse or crashes again, retire it and move to a different architecture family rather than returning to more JumpReLU-local tuning."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0077.stdout.log:784:research/history_archive/11_20260322_021455/logs/agent_action_0021.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"JumpReLU local search appears exhausted, and reverting to the fundamentally different plain top-k SAE may provide a cleaner reconstruction-support tradeoff at K=128 under the same strong optimization settings, serving as a robust architecture reset after the failed gated launch attempts.","summary":"Switch from stalled JumpReLU tuning to a proxy top-k architecture run at K=128 while keeping the strongest validated training settings fixed for a clean architecture comparison.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"quality","family_name":"topk","family_stage":"mainline_comparison","self_review":"This satisfies the requirement to try a fundamentally different architecture approach after prolonged stagnation, while avoiding the invalid gated-only overrides that caused recent crashes. The main risk is top-k underperforming JumpReLU, but it is the cleanest valid architecture pivot available without editing code.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"topk"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"8"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"1.6e-3"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"},{"key":"K","value":"128"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Recent gated attempts failed at the launcher interface due to invalid env overrides, so a different architecture probe should avoid architecture-specific override keys unless confirmed valid.","Eight non-improving rounds indicate the current JumpReLU search direction is fundamentally stalled.","This round uses the plain top-k SAE as a clean architecture reset under the same best-known training regime to measure whether JumpReLU-specific gating is part of the quality bottleneck."],"next_hypotheses":["If top-k improves proxy FVU, promote to full and then stabilize the top-k family before revisiting cost or smaller-K tradeoffs.","If top-k is competitive but not better, compare its runtime and stability against JumpReLU to decide whether it is a better base for further architecture work.","If top-k is clearly worse, conclude that a stronger new family is needed and plan a code-backed architecture exploration round rather than more JumpReLU-local parameter sweeps."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
research/history/logs/agent_round_0077.stdout.log:870:research/history_archive/12_20260323_013532/logs/agent_action_0085_repair_1.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"The crash is a pure registration blocker: `residual_vq` is missing from the architecture whitelist in `sparsify/config.py` and likely not wired into the constructor dispatch in `sparsify/sparse_coder.py`. Patch only that registration path so the unchanged `K=32, EF=12`, `signum`, `lr=1.6e-3`, `auxk_alpha=0` proxy can instantiate.","summary":"Apply a narrow registration repair for `residual_vq` inside `sparsify/` and relaunch the exact same proxy target. Do not change the experiment recipe; only make the architecture name legal and constructible by the existing config/factory flow.","change_type":"edit_sae_code","experiment_tier":"proxy","expected_win":"Convert the current unknown-architecture crash into a real startup/training signal for the original `residual_vq` target.","family_name":"residual_vq","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This is a tight repair scoped directly to the observed `Unknown architecture` error. It preserves the original experiment exactly and avoids mixing in any new search variable.","needs_sanity":true,"env_overrides":{"ARCHITECTURE":"residual_vq","K":"32","EXPANSION_FACTOR":"12","OPTIMIZER":"signum","LR":"1.6e-3","AUXK_ALPHA":"0"},"touched_files":["sparsify/config.py","sparsify/sparse_coder.py","sparsify/residual_vq.py"],"notes_to_memory":["Round 85 repair attempt 1 targets only the concrete registration failure for `residual_vq`; no recipe changes are allowed.","Observed blocker: `ValueError: Unknown architecture: 'residual_vq'` raised in `sparsify/config.py::__post_init__` before training starts.","Keep follow-up repairs, if needed, constrained to making the existing architecture constructible under the unchanged launcher path."],"next_hypotheses":["If the registration repair works and the run completes, evaluate `residual_vq` on quality before any further edits.","If a new concrete constructor or DDP compatibility error appears after registration is fixed, do one more pinpoint repair on the same target.","If the repaired prototype runs and is clearly weak, archive it on quality grounds rather than extending repair work."],"primary_variable":"code_fix"}
